<?xml version="1.0"?><collection name="D0817-B"><document name="APW_ENG_20051007.0807"><line>&quot;Armstrong still enjoys the presumption of innocence,&quot; he said in an interview on the sidelines of a meeting with Belgian business leaders.</line></document><document name="AFP_ENG_20050909.0570"><line>&quot;The Anderson ruling is very significant in that he has been someone who has been given credibility in newspapers in France like Le Monde and L'Equipe.&quot;</line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20050919.0941"><line>&quot;The investigation of the testing and the results that were published must logically start with the laboratory and WADA and we are waiting for a response from them to our questions.&quot;</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20051006.0136"><line>Armstrong, who could not be reached for comment on Thursday, has denied the charges, saying he is the victim of a &quot;witch hunt.&quot;</line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20051007.0807"><line>Both the International Cycling Union and the World Anti-Doping Agency have announced separate inquiries into the case, but Rogge said he prefers a fully independent probe.<annotation scu-count="2" sum-count="4" sums="0,19,43,48"><scu uid="46" label="International Cycling Union (UCI) investigating allegations of Armstrong EPO use" weight="3"/><scu uid="47" label="WADA investigates allegations" weight="2"/></annotation></line></document><document name="AFP_ENG_20050921.0518"><line>They also complain that the system used by the lab brings into doubt the whole procedure.</line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20050920.1234"><line>&quot;We tried to the best of our possibilities to provide the information that we have,&quot; Pound told a news conference on Tuesday after a meeting of WADA's executive committee.</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20051006.0136"><line>The governing agency for professional cycling appointed an independent investigator Thursday to look into accusations that the American cycling champion Lance Armstrong had used banned drugs.<annotation scu-count="1" sum-count="2" sums="51,55"><scu uid="46" label="International Cycling Union (UCI) investigating allegations of Armstrong EPO use" weight="3"/></annotation></line></document><document name="AFP_ENG_20050906.0396"><line>&quot;He could be feeling the need to prove to everyone that he is the strongest, and that it's not down to illegal substances.</line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20051007.0807"><line>Rogge questioned whether the samples belonged to Armstrong and whether they contained EPO.<annotation scu-count="1" sum-count="2" sums="32,57"><scu uid="39" label="The integrity and validity of the tests are questioned" weight="2"/></annotation></line></document><document name="AFP_ENG_20050906.0396"><line>That's normal.</line></document><document name="AFP_ENG_20050915.0700"><line>&quot;I am happy with the way my career went and I am happy with the way it ended.</line><line>&quot;I know if I go back there is no way I am going to get a fair shake in the lab, on the roadside, in the hotel, in my food.</line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20050919.0941"><line>Pound said last week he received a letter from UCI president Hein Verbruggen saying he had provided L'Equipe with forms indicating Armstrong had tested positive for EPO during his first Tour victory.</line></document><document name="AFP_ENG_20050909.0570"><line>Armstrong, who turns 34 on September 18, also won a summary judgement in a Texas court case that dismissed charges Armstrong defrauded and breached a contract with his former personal assistant, Mike Anderson.</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20050913.0357"><line>Armstrong said there are &quot;many factors&quot; for his being investigated in France, including the loss of dominance by French riders in the past two decades.<annotation scu-count="0" sum-count="1" sums="43"/></line><line>&quot;You do 'Larry King Live,&quot;' Armstrong said Tuesday, citing one Internet poll that showed 87 percent of the people believed him -- &quot;stateside.&quot;</line><line>It appears that Armstrong has a large tiger by the tail, in what he had depicted as a placid retirement.</line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20050919.0941"><line>UCI said it had not received enough information to make a judgment on the allegations.</line></document><document name="AFP_ENG_20050915.0700"><line>I got three kids in the pool right now and they are screaming my name.&quot;</line></document><document name="AFP_ENG_20050906.0396"><line>Anyway, he's still under contract with us till the end of 2006.&quot;</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20050913.0357"><line>A trial, scheduled for High Court in London on Nov. 6 involves his suit concerning excerpts from the book &quot;L.A.</line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20050920.1234"><line>&quot;I thought about sanctioning myself and decided against it,&quot; Pound quipped.</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20050913.0357"><line>&quot;That's the way I was raised,&quot; he said.</line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20050919.0941"><line>&quot;It has been three weeks... and WADA has failed, to date, to provide all the documents and information we have requested, which we need to conduct the investigation, even though WADA has stated its willingness to assist the UCI,&quot; the statement added.</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20050913.0357"><line>SCA has cited the book and other doubts as a reason for not paying.</line><line>It was hardly normal for a Tour leader to intervene in a harmless breakaway, but Armstrong had to aggress Simeoni.</line></document><document name="AFP_ENG_20050909.0570"><line>&quot;Today vindicates Lance and points out that the accusations he made against Lance were without merit in an American court.<annotation scu-count="0" sum-count="1" sums="5"/></line><line>&quot;I'm not willing to put a percentage on the chances but I will no longer rule it out.&quot;</line></document><document name="AFP_ENG_20050906.0396"><line>That said, we speak for 15 minutes on the phone every day, and for 13 of those we talk about cycling.&quot;</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20051006.0136"><line>If appointing this group helps, we're for it.&quot;</line></document><document name="AFP_ENG_20050921.0518"><line>&quot;Obviously, the lab itself does not have the right to publicly confirm or comment upon analyses considering these were done illegally and their identification was made in violation of the guarantee of confidentiality.</line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20050919.0941"><line>Last month, L'Equipe published evidence allegedly showing that six of Armstrong's frozen urine samples from 1999 came back positive for endurance-boosting EPO when they were retested last year.</line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20050920.1234"><line>&quot;We are unable to answer questions of what may have been on the minds of the UCI or the lab.&quot;</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20050913.0357"><line>The International Cycling Union, known as UCI, which has belatedly ratcheted up its testing process in recent years, appeared to shrug off the charges last week, lacking further proof.</line></document><document name="AFP_ENG_20050915.0700"><line>Until 2001, cycling's international governing body did not use a urine test for EPO, which builds endurance by boosting the oxygen-carrying capacity of blood.</line></document><document name="AFP_ENG_20050909.0570"><line>&quot;This totally vindicates Lance's position.</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20050913.0357"><line>Mostly, Lance Armstrong's retirement sounds much like his racing career.<annotation scu-count="0" sum-count="1" sums="32"/></line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20051006.0136"><line>The urine samples had been saved, frozen and recently tested for a research project.<annotation scu-count="0" sum-count="1" sums="29"/></line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20051007.0807"><line>Backup &quot;B&quot; samples from 1999 were frozen and tested for EPO last year.</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20050913.0357"><line>He pursues people.</line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20050920.1234"><line>Pound said this year FIFA risked expulsion from the Olympics because it failed to accept two-year bans for serious doping offenses.</line></document><document name="AFP_ENG_20050915.0700"><line>On August 23, L'Equipe reported with a front page headline &quot;The Armstrong Lie&quot; that six of Armstrong's urine samples tested positive for EPO during the 1999 race.</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20051006.0136"><line>&quot;There's no way I could go back there.</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20050913.0357"><line>Armstrong is not about to lose any of his seven championships, nor should he.<annotation scu-count="1" sum-count="1" sums="8"><scu uid="41" label="No action to be taken against Armstrong" weight="2"/></annotation></line></document><document name="AFP_ENG_20050906.0396"><line>&quot;He's missing racing, and everything that goes with it.</line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20051007.0807"><line>Cycling did not test for EPO until 2001.</line></document><document name="AFP_ENG_20050921.0518"><line>Pound said that although WADA did not have all the facts of the case there did not appear to be any ethical rules broken by the French laboratory.</line></document><document name="AFP_ENG_20050915.0700"><line>Armstrong said Thursday the integrity of the international anti-doping system is at stake because of the way the samples were mis-handled and the manner in which the information passed on to the newspaper.</line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20050920.1234"><line>World Anti-Doping Agency chief Dick Pound denied claims by the International Cycling Union that WADA withheld information for the probe into whether Lance Armstrong used banned substances during the 1999 Tour de France.<annotation scu-count="1" sum-count="7" sums="11,14,21,23,37,43,6"><scu uid="54" label="UCI accuses WADA of withholding information and blocking UCI's investigation" weight="2"/></annotation></line></document><document name="AFP_ENG_20050921.0518"><line>&quot;Confidentiality requires extra safeguards given the sensitive nature of these tests.</line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20050919.0941"><line>&quot;Mr. Verbruggen has never been involved personally, contrary to what Mr. Pound said in another statement.</line></document><document name="AFP_ENG_20050921.0518"><line>&quot;This is simply unacceptable.</line></document><document name="AFP_ENG_20050915.0700"><line>&quot;We believe in standing up for what is right,&quot; Armstrong said.</line></document><document name="AFP_ENG_20050921.0518"><line>The demand, in a letter to Dick Pound, the president of the World Anti-Doping Agency (WADA) and obtained by AFP, insists the laboratory broke a host of rules set down in the World Anti-Doping Code.</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20051006.0136"><line>Even though the samples were anonymous, the article said paperwork linked the coded samples to Armstrong.</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20050913.0357"><line>&quot;I'm looking forward to it,&quot; Armstrong said.</line><line>People pursue him.</line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20051007.0807"><line>Any sanctions are unlikely because the original &quot;A&quot; samples were used up and can't be verified for confirmation.</line><line>He hopes WADA will come up with a viable procedure within the coming months.</line></document><document name="AFP_ENG_20050906.0396"><line>&quot;I'm thinking about it,&quot; the Austin American-Statesman quoted Armstrong as saying.</line><line>Maybe he's thinking about taking some kind of sporting revenge for the allegations of doping that he's had to hear day after day.<annotation scu-count="0" sum-count="1" sums="8"/></line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20050913.0357"><line>Let's say I took EPO in 1999 and didn't take it from 2000 to 2005.</line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20050920.1234"><line>&quot;We're a bit nervous about the way this is going, so while we're willing to be helpful in the context of a full investigation, we're not there to participate in something that amounts to a search of how the information made its way in the public domain.&quot;</line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20050919.0941"><line>The International Cycling Union denies accusations that its president supplied a French sports newspaper with documents which it used to accuse Lance Armstrong of doping at the 1999 Tour de France.<annotation scu-count="1" sum-count="8" sums="23,25,3,41,42,44,49,5"><scu uid="56" label="ICU's Verbruggen denies having leaked information about Armstrong's tests to L'Equipe" weight="1"/></annotation></line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20050913.0357"><line>During the 2004 Tour, Armstrong chased down Filippo Simeoni, an Italian cyclist who had testified against Armstrong's adviser, Dr. Michele Ferrari, who has since been implicated in unethical practices.</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20051006.0136"><line>The governing body, the International Cycling Union, said that Emile Vrijman and his law firm, Lamsma Veldstra &amp; Lobe, based in Rotterdam, the Netherlands, would investigate claims by the French newspaper L'Equipe that six samples of Armstrong's frozen urine from the 1999 Tour de France had tested positive for the hormone erythropoietin, or EPO, which aids a cyclist's endurance.<annotation scu-count="0" sum-count="2" sums="13,29"/></line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20050913.0357"><line>&quot;There will be cross-examination,&quot; Armstrong said.</line><line>&quot;EPO is a powerful drug,&quot; Armstrong said Tuesday.</line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20051007.0807"><line>He also questioned UCI's willingness to fully investigate the allegations.</line></document><document name="AFP_ENG_20050906.0396"><line>He follows the team's progress closely and it's sure that he's still hungry for success.</line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20050920.1234"><line>Separately, Pound said on Tuesday that FIFA was inching closer to compliance with WADA's anti-doping code after the soccer body revised its rules to allow WADA to appeal any FIFA rulings to the Court of Arbitration for Sport.</line></document><document name="AFP_ENG_20050921.0518"><line>&quot;In this case, it appears that numerous violations of the World Anti-Doping Code have been committed and that the most basic guarantees, for which every athlete has a right, have been held up to ridicule,&quot; said the letter, signed by ASOIF president Denis Oswald and Sergei Bubka, head of the IOC's athletes commission.</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20050913.0357"><line>He has generally been well received by French cycling fans by the side of the road, however, and claiming French anti-Americanism is not fair.</line><line>The book contains voluminous allusions to drug use in cycling that resulted in the deaths of dozens of young riders, plus various scandals and suspensions.</line><line>&quot;There are other countries in Europe,&quot; Armstrong said Tuesday, referring to the challenging national races of Italy or Spain.</line></document><document name="AFP_ENG_20050915.0700"><line>Once again Armstrong vehemently denied the allegations on Thursday.<annotation scu-count="1" sum-count="2" sums="19,48"><scu uid="55" label="Lance Armstrong continues to deny doping charges" weight="1"/></annotation></line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20050913.0357"><line>Pay the money.&quot;</line></document><document name="AFP_ENG_20050909.0570"><line>Cycling's world governing body found nothing that could be used as proof of wrongdoing by Armstrong and no reason to condemn him, wondering instead who leaked Armstrong's identity and why his sample was chosen for testing.<annotation scu-count="0" sum-count="1" sums="29"/></line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20050913.0357"><line>My performance never dropped off.</line><line>At first, it sounded like a delicious prank -- Lance Armstrong riding again in France, just to annoy his critics.</line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20051007.0807"><line>But if they differ it would be good to go to the independent observers,&quot; he said.</line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20050920.1234"><line>Pound said WADA was concerned about the &quot;accusatory approach&quot; by UCI, which accused WADA of withholding information.</line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20051007.0807"><line>On Thursday, the UCI said it had appointed Dutch lawyer Emile Vrijman and his firm to conduct an independent investigation into L'Equipe's allegations.</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20050913.0357"><line>When Armstrong retired, the 1999 B samples somehow materialized at L'Equipe.<annotation scu-count="0" sum-count="1" sums="5"/></line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20051007.0807"><line>Armstrong denied using banned drugs and said he was the victim of a &quot;witch hunt.&quot;<annotation scu-count="1" sum-count="1" sums="6"><scu uid="55" label="Lance Armstrong continues to deny doping charges" weight="1"/></annotation></line></document><document name="AFP_ENG_20050921.0518"><line>&quot;These events not only cast serious doubt on the credibility of the French anti-doping system, but also on the entire world-wide anti-doping fight if such blatant transgressions are not rectified and those responsible properly disciplined,&quot; they complained.</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20051006.0136"><line>I would be crazy.&quot;</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20050913.0357"><line>The retroactive tests were done only on the B urine samples that had been retained from 1999.</line></document><document name="AFP_ENG_20050909.0570"><line>A UCI statement said no action would be taken against Armstrong over claims by the French sports daily L'Equipe that his 1999 urine samples tested positive for the banned blood booster EPO (erythropoietin).<annotation scu-count="0" sum-count="2" sums="16,29"/></line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20050919.0941"><line>It also criticized L'Equipe for targeting Armstrong, and criticized Pound for making public statements on the &quot;likely guilt of the athlete&quot; without knowing all the facts.</line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20051007.0807"><line>He insisted Armstrong's rights had not properly been respected.</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20050913.0357"><line>There are, however, enough claims and rumors and old enemies and circumstantial evidence going around to do continued harm to Armstrong's image in his home country -- the cancer survivor who won the Tour seven times and has built a foundation to fight the disease that almost killed him.</line><line>He is battling for his reputation as he often attacked a competitor on the slopes of France.</line><line>&quot;That's a question of Texas contract law,&quot; Armstrong said.</line></document><document name="AFP_ENG_20050915.0700"><line>I would be crazy, so why don't we all just say I am not going back.&quot;</line></document><document name="AFP_ENG_20050906.0396"><line>Johan Bruyneel, the 33-year-old Armstrong's team manager at Discovery Channel, admitted that nothing concrete had been decided but the door was still open for a return.</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20051006.0136"><line>After the article in L'Equipe appeared, Armstrong said he was considering racing again, but later changed his mind.</line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20050919.0941"><line>&quot;We're waiting to see whether they have a commitment to get at the truth and the whole truth before we decide to participate further in the investigation,&quot; Pound said at the time.</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20051006.0136"><line>&quot;The UCI expects all relevant parties to fully co-operate with the investigation.&quot;</line></document><document name="AFP_ENG_20050915.0453"><line>Pound told a press conference in Montreal on Thursday that it was Verbruggen who had given information about Armstrong to the French daily, which reported on August 23 that urine samples from Armstrong's first of seven Tour de France wins in 1999 contained traces of banned blood-boosting drug EPO.<annotation scu-count="1" sum-count="2" sums="33,41"><scu uid="53" label="WADA claims ICU's Verbruggen leaked information to L'Equipe about Armstrong 1999 EPO results" weight="2"/></annotation></line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20051007.0807"><line>IOC president Jacques Rogge called Friday for outside &quot;independent observers&quot; to investigate allegations that seven-time Tour de France champion Lance Armstrong tested positive for EPO at the 1999 race.<annotation scu-count="1" sum-count="10" sums="0,14,19,21,37,44,48,55,57,6"><scu uid="38" label="IOC investigates allegations of Armstrong EPO use" weight="2"/></annotation></line></document><document name="AFP_ENG_20050915.0700"><line>Armstrong claims he spoke too soon when he said earlier this month that he was prepared to make a comeback just to spite French organizers of the world's most challenging bike race.</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20050913.0357"><line>Since his last ride up the Champs-Elysees, on July 24, Armstrong has proposed to his girlfriend, Sheryl Crow, spent time with his three children, and, through the Lance Armstrong Foundation, donated $500,000 to cancer victims uprooted by Hurricane Katrina.</line></document><document name="AFP_ENG_20050906.0396"><line>Asked how serious he was about another Tour, Armstrong replied: &quot;I'm exercising every day.&quot;</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20050913.0357"><line>Armstrong might be liable for court costs, which could amount to more than $1 million, if he dropped the Sunday Times suit.<annotation scu-count="0" sum-count="1" sums="18"/></line></document><document name="AFP_ENG_20050909.0570"><line>Armstrong's engagement to Crow was announced Monday, a day before the US cycling legend stated that he might seek an eighth consecutive Tour victory next July as a result of the latest accusations.</line><line>Seven-time Tour de France winner Lance Armstrong was given major support in his fight against doping allegations on Friday by the International Cycling Union (UCI) and a Texas legal triumph.<annotation scu-count="1" sum-count="11" sums="10,11,20,25,32,36,40,42,43,49,55"><scu uid="43" label="International Cycling Union supports Lance Armstrong's fight against doping allegations" weight="1"/></annotation></line></document><document name="AFP_ENG_20050915.0700"><line>These were not the first allegations of drug use against Armstrong since his recovery from testicular cancer in 1996.<annotation scu-count="0" sum-count="1" sums="51"/></line></document><document name="AFP_ENG_20050906.0396"><line>The Texan has vehemently denied taking any performance-enhancing drugs however a number of experts and former employees have come out of the woodwork to denounce the Texan champion.</line></document><document name="AFP_ENG_20050909.0570"><line>&quot;Im pleased that the UCI seems to be asking many of the right questions.&quot;</line></document><document name="AFP_ENG_20050921.0518"><line>Oswald and Bubka warned that athletes may be wary of competing in France in the future &quot;if their due rights are so carelessly disregarded and there is the possibility that they too could find themselves facing accusations at the end of procedures to which they were not a party.&quot;</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20050913.0357"><line>American sports fans are only now developing their cynical side after recent developments in baseball.</line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20051007.0807"><line>&quot;I have asked that an independent inquiry be started to pinpoint the different responsibilities,&quot; Rogge said, adding he hoped &quot;the inquiry, if possible, would also be able to show whether the sample was positive.&quot;<annotation scu-count="1" sum-count="1" sums="0"><scu uid="38" label="IOC investigates allegations of Armstrong EPO use" weight="2"/></annotation></line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20050913.0357"><line>The paper is owned by the same corporation that runs the Tour de France, which made millions of dollars from American tourism and corporate involvement during the Armstrong years.</line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20050919.0941"><line>&quot;If one of the issues that the UCI wants to explore is how some of this information became public, that's fine.</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20050913.0357"><line>Armstrong concedes that the L'Equipe charges may be raised in some of his legal cases.<annotation scu-count="0" sum-count="1" sums="32"/></line><line>Still, doubts have been raised.</line></document><document name="AFP_ENG_20050921.0518"><line>&quot;WADAs International Standard for Laboratories goes on to say that laboratories must use a unique internal code for each sample, that no information that could link an athlete with an individual result may be included in its reports to WADA and, in general, that athlete confidentiality is a key concern for all laboratories engaged in doping control cases.</line><line>&quot;However, in this case, the results of the analysis that have been done for research purposes, not even anti-doping control purposes, have been reported not with the internal laboratory code (which was not even necessary for reporting research results), but with the sample code!</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20050913.0357"><line>Stapleton and Armstrong have been highly critical of Richard W. Pound, the head of the World Anti-Doping Agency, for calling for further investigation of the 1999 tests.<annotation scu-count="1" sum-count="2" sums="3,35"><scu uid="47" label="WADA investigates allegations" weight="2"/></annotation></line></document><document name="AFP_ENG_20050915.0700"><line>He also isn't ruling out sabotage.</line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20050920.1234"><line>The UCI urged WADA to censure Pound or assign someone else to the case.</line><line>WADA also announced that it approved the 2006 list of prohibited substances and methods, which would be published before October and go into effect on Jan. 1, 2006.</line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20050919.0941"><line>&quot;It is essential for the WADA Board to hold Mr. Pound accountable and... act swiftly and definitively to establish that conduct of this type will not be tolerated.&quot;</line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20050920.1234"><line>He said he was puzzled by a request from cycling's world governing body for information on Armstrong because WADA did not exist at the time of the alleged doping incidents.<annotation scu-count="0" sum-count="2" sums="38,8"/></line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20051006.0136"><line>Armstrong, 34, the seven-time winner of the Tour de France bicycle race, retired from competitive cycling in July after his seventh consecutive victory.<annotation scu-count="0" sum-count="1" sums="43"/></line></document><document name="AFP_ENG_20050906.0396"><line>&quot;But don't make me say that Lance has already decided what he will do with the rest of his career.</line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20050920.1234"><line>The arrangement amounted to &quot;a good decision&quot; avoiding future public confrontation, he said.</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20050913.0357"><line>At the moment, Armstrong is combating the Aug. 23 article in L'Equipe, the French sports daily, that said six of his 1999 samples tested for EPO, the blood-boosting drug, appeared positive in a recent test.<annotation scu-count="0" sum-count="2" sums="3,51"/></line><line>But I only got faster.&quot;</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20051006.0136"><line>But Dan Osipow, a spokesman for Armstrong's racing team's sponsor, Discovery Channel, said: &quot;We're pleased that the UCI is forming this investigation unit to try to get to the bottom of this case.</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20050913.0357"><line>In reality, it is a terrible idea.</line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20050919.0941"><line>UCI also called on WADA to either censure its chief or assign someone else to deal with this case.</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20050913.0357"><line>It is likely that some people critical of Armstrong in the book will be testifying.</line></document><document name="AFP_ENG_20050915.0700"><line>Armstrong, who retired after his seventh consecutive Tour de France victory in July, has been accused of using banned blood booster EPO (erythropoietin) by French sports daily L'Equipe in an article which showed details of 1999 drugs tests.<annotation scu-count="0" sum-count="2" sums="11,22"/></line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20050920.1234"><line>On Monday, the UCI denied Pound's assertion that its president Hein Verbruggen supplied information to the French newspaper L'Equipe, which reported last month that Armstrong's urine samples from the 1999 race contained traces of the banned endurance-enhancing drug EPO.<annotation scu-count="1" sum-count="3" sums="16,35,48"><scu uid="56" label="ICU's Verbruggen denies having leaked information about Armstrong's tests to L'Equipe" weight="1"/></annotation></line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20050919.0941"><line>However, it is also apparent that the reporters were given at least five and perhaps 15 of Lance Armstrong's doping control forms from the 1999 Tour de France, and it is certain that those forms did not come from the UCI.&quot;</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20050913.0357"><line>The other impending legal case involves Armstrong's suit to claim the $5 million bonus for winning his sixth consecutive Tour in 2004, as guaranteed by an insurance company, SCA Promotions, in Texas.</line></document><document name="AFP_ENG_20050921.0518"><line>&quot;This says a lot about the complicity and the professional ethics of those involved.</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20051006.0136"><line>Vrijman is the former director of the National Anti-Doping Agency in the Netherlands.</line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20051007.0807"><line>The leaders of WADA and UCI have been engaged in a bitter feud over the case.</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20050913.0357"><line>Just as he was on his bicycle, Armstrong, in the first months of retirement, is a ferocious legal competitor.</line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20051007.0807"><line>&quot;If they have the same conclusion, no problem.</line></document><document name="AFP_ENG_20050915.0700"><line>&quot;I am going to say this in just a few words.</line></document><document name="AFP_ENG_20050915.0453"><line>He at least has shown all six (doping test forms signed by Armstrong) to the journalist and he gave the journalist at least one copy.&quot;</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20051006.0136"><line>&quot;There is no way I could go to France and get a fair shake on the roads, in doping control or in the labs,&quot; Armstrong told reporters last month from his home in Austin, Texas.</line></document><document name="AFP_ENG_20050915.0700"><line>A 2004 book by former L'Equipe journalist Pierre Ballester entitled &quot;LA Confidential: The Secrets of Lance Armstrong,&quot; cited one of the cyclist's former assistants claiming Armstrong once asked her to dispose of used syringes.</line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20050919.0941"><line>Pound questioned the UCI's willingness to fully investigate L'Equipe's allegations and wondered whether the cycling body was merely looking for a &quot;scapegoat.&quot;</line></document><document name="AFP_ENG_20050906.0396"><line>Bruyneel, who has orchestrated Armstrong's career since the American returned to cycling after his successful recovery from cancer in 1998, suggested Armstrong simply missed racing.</line></document><document name="AFP_ENG_20050915.0453"><line>Armstrong has continually denied he took performance-enhancing substances and pointed out proper procedures had not been followed and no B sample was provided.</line></document><document name="AFP_ENG_20050915.0700"><line>The 33-year-old Armstrong believes there are too many people who are against him in France to make it possible for him to go back and ride.</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20050913.0357"><line>So far it has been published only in French.</line></document><document name="AFP_ENG_20050915.0700"><line>&quot;I am sick of dealing with this (expletive).</line><line>I am not coming back,&quot; Armstrong said.</line></document><document name="AFP_ENG_20050921.0518"><line>The IOC Athletes Commission and the Summer Olympic sports (ASOIF) have demanded the French lab that claimed Tour de France winner Lance Armstrong had tested positive for doping in 1999 be suspended.<annotation scu-count="1" sum-count="9" sums="12,14,19,23,35,37,43,44,57"><scu uid="40" label="Olympic organizations demand the French lab be suspended" weight="2"/></annotation></line></document><document name="AFP_ENG_20050906.0396"><line>&quot;There will always be a place on the team for him, if he decides to come back.</line></document><document name="AFP_ENG_20050915.0700"><line>&quot;But today I am dealing with all this again.</line></document><document name="AFP_ENG_20050921.0518"><line>ASOIF and the athletes commission claim that the tests carried out by the Ch√¢tenay-Malabry laboratory on Armstrong's sample were illegal.</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20050913.0357"><line>Obviously, I'm not saying I did.</line></document><document name="AFP_ENG_20050921.0518"><line>&quot;The consequences of a positive test for an athlete are so severe that the procedures that lead to such a result must adhere to extremely strict rules and the results must be based on irrefutable evidence.</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20050913.0357"><line>&quot;You sit there and tell your side of it.&quot;</line></document><document name="AFP_ENG_20050906.0396"><line>Seven-time Tour de France winner Lance Armstrong is considering coming out of retirement in a bid to take revenge on the hosts of the world's biggest race following a spate of doping accusations, an Austin, Texas newspaper reported Tuesday.<annotation scu-count="0" sum-count="8" sums="10,13,25,33,36,40,43,5"/></line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20051007.0807"><line>UCI denied Pound's accusations and claimed he was blocking its investigation by withholding information.<annotation scu-count="1" sum-count="2" sums="19,48"><scu uid="54" label="UCI accuses WADA of withholding information and blocking UCI's investigation" weight="2"/></annotation></line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20050919.0941"><line>The UCI said it was conducting an investigation at WADA's request.<annotation scu-count="1" sum-count="1" sums="32"><scu uid="46" label="International Cycling Union (UCI) investigating allegations of Armstrong EPO use" weight="3"/></annotation></line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20050920.1234"><line>WADA said in a news release that the new list was a &quot;consolidation list and includes only minor modifications.&quot;</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20050913.0357"><line>Now that Armstrong has taken on institutional France as the source of the latest drug charges against him, who knows what plastic shopping bag or stray foot might be lurking amidst the swarms on the mountainsides?</line><line>The champion who would not go away.</line></document><document name="AFP_ENG_20050909.0570"><line>He's pleased,&quot; said Bill Stapleton, a lawyer for Armstrong.</line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20050919.0941"><line>But we're not prepared to sit by and participate in an investigation that focuses only on how the information became public.&quot;</line></document><document name="AFP_ENG_20050909.0570"><line>&quot;Im pleased the UCI is investigating this entire matter thoroughly because any professional investigation will reveal that the allegations made by a French sports tabloid have no basis because I never used any performance enhancing drugs,&quot; Armstrong said in a statement.</line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20051007.0807"><line>Rogge also said he wants to extend to all sporting federations the system of keeping doping samples for eight years for possible retroactive sanctions.<annotation scu-count="0" sum-count="1" sums="38"/></line></document><document name="AFP_ENG_20050909.0570"><line>The legal fight included Anderson claims that he found items in a Spanish apartment linking Armstrong to banned substances and that Armstrong avoided a 2004 random doping test.<annotation scu-count="0" sum-count="1" sums="47"/></line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20051007.0807"><line>In August, the French sports paper L'Equipe published documentation alleging six of Armstrong's frozen urine samples from the 1999 Tour came back positive for endurance-boosting EPO when they were retested last year.<annotation scu-count="0" sum-count="3" sums="29,43,49"/></line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20050913.0357"><line>The release of this data, whether accurate or not, violates all standards of confidentiality and control that should govern drug testing.</line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20051007.0807"><line>Last month, WADA chief Dick Pound accused former UCI president Hein Verbruggen of leaking documents about the alleged positive tests to L'Equipe.</line></document><document name="AFP_ENG_20050915.0453"><line>Since the fall-out from the allegations, Verbruggen has never publicly pointed the finger at the American.</line></document><document name="AFP_ENG_20050921.0518"><line>&quot;The results have been reported in a way so as to be able to identify the race, the day other samples were taken and, based on the doping control form containing the sample code, the identity of the athletes tested!</line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20050919.0941"><line>Also on Monday, the UCI said World Anti-Doping Agency chief Dick Pound was blocking its investigation by withholding information.</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20050913.0357"><line>Many Europeans assume that cyclists rely on chemicals in one form or another.</line></document><document name="AFP_ENG_20050915.0700"><line>L'Equipe reported that positive results came solely from B samples, the second of two samples used in doping tests.</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20051006.0136"><line>&quot;The UCI has entrusted Mr. Vrijman and his law firm the task to undertake a comprehensive investigation regarding all issues concerning the testing conducted by the French laboratory of urine samples from the 1999 Tour de France,&quot; the cycling union said in a statement on its Web site.</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20050913.0357"><line>&quot;What's the deal?</line><line>Armstrong, who has vehemently denied ever using performance-enhancing drugs, is now vowing to pursue two cases even though they could very well open unpleasant testimony.</line><line>A subsequent article in The New York Times revealed a collegial controversy among scientists about the current test for EPO.</line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20051007.0807"><line>&quot;It can be solved quickly,&quot; he said.</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20051006.0136"><line>Armstrong, a cancer survivor, was on a 3,300-mile bicycle ride across the United States on Thursday helping to raise money for cancer research.</line></document><document name="AFP_ENG_20050915.0700"><line>&quot;I opened it up a few weeks ago by saying I might come back,&quot; Armstrong said.</line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20051007.0807"><line>Rogge wants a group of &quot;independent observers&quot; who are linked to WADA but operate autonomously to settle the issues if the UCI and WADA investigations lead to different conclusions.</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20050913.0357"><line>The last thing Armstrong, the seven-time winner of the Tour de France, needs next year is to be racing downhill in the Alps or the Pyrenees.</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20051006.0136"><line>The cycling union did not test for EPO until 2001.</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20050913.0357"><line>&quot;The question is not about me but about the process and the ethics,&quot; Armstrong said Tuesday in a telephone interview.</line></document><document name="AFP_ENG_20050915.0700"><line>American cycling hero Lance Armstrong said Thursday he is content to stay retired and has no plans to go for an eighth straight Tour de France title.<annotation scu-count="0" sum-count="2" sums="12,21"/></line></document><document name="AFP_ENG_20050909.0570"><line>Capping a week that included his engagement to rock singer Sheryl Crow and hints at a possible 2006 return from retirement, Armstrong had his denials of taking performance-enhancing drugs strongly bolstered in separate findings.</line></document><document name="AFP_ENG_20050915.0700"><line>&quot;There is no way I can go back there (France).</line></document><document name="AFP_ENG_20050906.0396"><line>&quot;He (Armstrong) got back on the bike to train three weeks after the end of the Tour de France.</line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20050920.1234"><line>&quot;We were only formed after these events took place in 1999,&quot; Pound said.</line></document><document name="AFP_ENG_20050906.0396"><line>Armstrong retired in July after winning his seventh straight Tour de France but expectations of relaxing holidays with his three kids and his new fiancee, rock star Sheryl Crow, have been tempered by a spate of doping allegations.<annotation scu-count="0" sum-count="1" sums="40"/></line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20050919.0941"><line>&quot;Mr. Pound's transparently erroneous statements about the UCI being the source of the forms are difficult to explain, except that they appear to be an attempt by Mr. Pound to draw attention away from his efforts to obstruct and delay the UCI investigation,&quot; UCI said in a statement.</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20050913.0357"><line>&quot;Some say it makes you 10 percent faster.</line></document><document name="AFP_ENG_20050915.0453"><line>WADA boss Dick Pound has claimed UCI head Hein Verbruggen tipped off L'Equipe in the Armstrong doping case.<annotation scu-count="1" sum-count="7" sums="16,19,20,32,48,51,57"><scu uid="53" label="WADA claims ICU's Verbruggen leaked information to L'Equipe about Armstrong 1999 EPO results" weight="2"/></annotation></line></document><document name="AFP_ENG_20050906.0396"><line>&quot;I'm thinking it's the best way to piss (the French) off.&quot;</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20051006.0136"><line>The cycling union appointed Vrijman on Sept. 30, but did not disclose the information on its Web site until Thursday.</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20050913.0357"><line>They say the B samples should never have been released and are unreliable, six years later, given the upgraded testing in recent years.</line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20050919.0941"><line>The seven-time Tour de France champion denied ever using banned drugs, and said he was the victim of a &quot;witch hunt.&quot;<annotation scu-count="1" sum-count="1" sums="6"><scu uid="55" label="Lance Armstrong continues to deny doping charges" weight="1"/></annotation></line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20050913.0357"><line>He is nothing if not combative.</line></document><document name="AFP_ENG_20050915.0700"><line>I have nothing to hide,&quot; Armstrong said.<annotation scu-count="0" sum-count="1" sums="21"/></line></document><document name="AFP_ENG_20050906.0396"><line>&quot;We could decide during our training camp in December (in the United States), which will be decisive (for the Tour),&quot; Bruyneel told the Belgian news agency Belga.</line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20050920.1234"><line>Armstrong has denied ever using banned drugs, and said he was the victim of a &quot;witch hunt&quot; after the article was published.<annotation scu-count="1" sum-count="1" sums="6"><scu uid="55" label="Lance Armstrong continues to deny doping charges" weight="1"/></annotation></line></document><document name="AFP_ENG_20050915.0453"><line>When asked if Verbruggen had given information to French daily L'Equipe, Pound said: &quot;Yes.</line></document><document name="AFP_ENG_20050906.0396"><line>Armstrong told the newspaper he had been thinking about a comeback for only the past two weeks, since French sports daily L'Equipe reported on August 23 that urine samples taken from Armstrong in 1999 during his first Tour triumph tested positive for the banned substance EPO.<annotation scu-count="0" sum-count="2" sums="22,29"/></line></document><document name="AFP_ENG_20050909.0570"><line>&quot;The recent smear campaign out of France has awoken my competitive side,&quot; Armstrong said.</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20050913.0357"><line>&quot;My lawyers tell me they do this all the time.&quot;</line><line>Confidentiel: Les Secrets de Lance Armstrong,&quot; published in The Sunday Times of London in 2004.</line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20051007.0807"><line>The cycling body said WADA's investigation was flawed because it was an &quot;involved party.&quot;</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20050913.0357"><line>In recent days, he has appeared at a testimonial to his blocking back, George Hincapie, in South Carolina on Saturday; rooted for his peer, Andre Agassi, at the U.S. Open in New York on Sunday; then jetted out to Sun Valley, Idaho, to cycle with his pal Robin Williams.</line><line>&quot;But Lance feels he was defamed by The Sunday Times,&quot; Bill Stapleton, Armstrong's agent, said Tuesday.</line></document></collection>